  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Fair trade for African Blackwood: achieving self-sufficiency - phase 2</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Rare hardwoods such as African blackwood are perfect for making musical instruments and other high quality products. However, the communities living in the Tanzanian forests where it grows currently receive less than 1% of what it&#x2019;s really worth, and their average annual income is below 200 US dollars. Most of the money goes to sawmills and musical instrument manufacturers. This project works in 20 villages in southern Tanzania with local communities to ensure that they can sell their wood for fair prices; supporting them to earn up to 100 times more for their blackwood, and then spend it in a sustainable way. The villages will then be able to afford to pay for any support they need in the future without having to rely on charitable funds.</narrative>
  </description>
